// Researched content for mexico-cancun-riviera-maya-a. Written per property.
module.exports = {
  'unico-2087-hotel-riviera-maya': {
    activities: `UNICO 20°87° sits on a stretch of Akumal coast between Playa del Carmen and Tulum, and its identity is design-forward rather than mega-resort: two social pools (20.87 for music and daytime energy, Escondida for quiet) plus a spa. Off-site, Akumal's bay is a short drive for snorkeling with sea turtles, and both the Tulum ruins and Mayan cenotes are easily reached, along with day trips into Tulum town's restaurant scene. Four restaurants cover Mediterranean, Yucatecan, and Asian menus.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This adults-only boutique hotel is reached via Cancun International Airport, roughly an hour south along the coast in the Akumal area. It's built around a hacienda-modern aesthetic rather than a typical all-inclusive footprint, and the ratings reflect that: rooms, service, and cleanliness are all near the top of the market, while the beach itself is the one soft mark, typical of this rockier Akumal-to-Tulum shoreline. It suits couples wanting a quieter, design-led resort over a sprawling family property. November through April brings the driest, calmest weather and the lowest odds of sargassum seaweed on the sand.`,
  },
  'paradisus-la-perla': {
    activities: `La Perla is the adults-only wing of the Paradisus Playa del Carmen complex, and guests can also use the shared grounds and restaurants of its family-side counterpart, La Esmeralda. On site there's a swim-up bar, a gym, and an included dive program that can run out to reefs off Playa del Carmen and Cozumel's Palancar and Colombia walls. The wider destination adds cenote tours, Xcaret and Xel-Ha parks, and Tulum's ruins as easy day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Paradisus La Perla is on the Riviera Maya coast at Playa del Carmen, about 45 minutes from Cancun airport. It's a Meliá-brand Unlimited-Luxury property, geared to couples rather than families, with rooms, cleanliness, and service scoring well above the beach itself, which is a middling mark for this part of the coast. Value and location both score strongly, making it a reasonable step up from budget all-inclusives without the price of the very top tier. Plan for December through April for the calmest seas and least chance of seaweed; hurricane season runs June through November.`,
  },
  'sun-palace': {
    activities: `Sun Palace is an adults-only property in the Cancun Hotel Zone, sharing beach and grounds access with its sister Palace Resorts properties nearby. Watersports and fishing charters leave right from the beach, an on-site dive center arranges trips out to the Mesoamerican reef, and there's a spa, swim-up bar, and nightly entertainment. The location also makes it easy to get into downtown Cancun or out to Isla Mujeres by ferry for a day of snorkeling and beach-hopping.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Sun Palace sits directly on the Hotel Zone's beach strip, a short taxi ride from Cancun airport. It's couples-oriented, part of the Palace Resorts group, and its beach score is genuinely one of its strengths, unusual for a Hotel Zone property, alongside strong cleanliness and service marks; the pool rates a notch lower by comparison. It suits travelers who want classic Cancun nightlife and beach within reach rather than the quieter Riviera Maya towns further south. Visit November to April for drier weather, keeping in mind that Gulf-facing beaches here can see periodic sargassum in summer.`,
  },
  'hotel-xcaret-arte': {
    activities: `Hotel Xcaret Arte, open to guests 16 and up, is built around Grupo Xcaret's parks, and a stay includes unlimited entry to Xcaret, Xel-Ha, Xplor, and the group's other Riviera Maya parks and tours, from underground river swims to Xenotes cenote circuits. On property, the pool complex (rated among the best in the region) winds through the grounds river-style, alongside a spa, yoga classes, and evening shows. Playa del Carmen's Quinta Avenida and the ferry to Cozumel are both a short drive away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This art-themed property in Playa del Carmen is reached via Cancun airport, about 45 minutes north. It's the top-rated hotel in our database across nearly every category, food, atmosphere, room, and cleanliness among them, and the appeal is squarely about access to Grupo Xcaret's ecopark network rather than a conventional beach stay; the beach score, while decent, is not its headline. It works for older teens through adults rather than young families given the 16+ policy. Book park excursions early in the stay, and target the December to April dry season for the most comfortable park days.`,
  },
  'impression-moxche-by-secrets': {
    activities: `Impression Moxché occupies the more exclusive side of a dual-resort property with its sister Secrets Moxché next door, sharing an unusual layout of pools designed to evoke cenotes. Its own restaurants (including a rooftop and a beach club) are reserved for its guests, alongside a spa and nightly entertainment. Excursions from here run to Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue, Tulum's ruins and beach clubs, and the cenotes and reef dives that define this stretch of the Riviera Maya.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Opened in December 2022, Impression Moxché is part of the Hyatt Inclusive Collection (the Secrets brand) in Playa del Carmen, about 10 minutes from downtown and 45 minutes from Cancun airport. It's adults-only and rated near the top of the market for food, room, cleanliness, and service, with a noticeably softer beach score, a fair trade for guests prioritizing the pool-and-suite experience over sand. It suits couples wanting a newer, five-diamond-level property rather than an established classic. Aim for the dry season, November through April, and note that this stretch of coast is seaweed-prone in mid-summer.`,
  },
  'akumal-bay-beach-and-wellness-resort': {
    activities: `This resort sits directly on Akumal Bay, one of the Riviera Maya's best-known spots to snorkel alongside sea turtles just offshore, and the beach and dive program are built around that. Kids' and teens' activities, a wellness-focused spa, yoga, and tennis round out the property, with a dive center running trips further along the reef. Tulum's ruins, the town's restaurants, and several nearby cenotes are all within a short drive.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Akumal Bay Beach & Wellness Resort is a family property reached via Tulum International Airport, closer than Cancun for this stretch of coast. Its strongest marks are value, location, and beach, reflecting the appeal of Akumal's calm, turtle-rich bay, while food and pool sit a step behind the rest of the ratings. It's well suited to families wanting a snorkeling-focused base rather than a Hotel Zone nightlife scene. Visit in the dry winter months for the calmest water and best turtle visibility; turtle nesting season runs May through October, when night access to parts of the beach may be restricted.`,
  },
  'hyatt-ziva-cancun': {
    activities: `Hyatt Ziva Cancun sits on one of the widest beaches in the Hotel Zone, with a waterpark and pool slides for younger kids, a separate adult pool, and both kids' and teens' clubs to free up parents' time. Evening entertainment and a nightclub cover the after-dark hours, while a swim-up bar, spa, and gym round out the day. The location puts Isla Mujeres ferries, Cancun's malls and marina, and the wider Hotel Zone's restaurants all within easy reach.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This family-oriented Hyatt sits mid-Hotel Zone in Cancun, a short ride from the international airport. Its ratings are strong across the board, with location, cleanliness, and room quality leading, and beach and food both solid rather than standout, typical for a large family resort at this price point. It's built for families with kids of varying ages given the layered kids'/teens' club structure, though couples are just as comfortable here. Late fall through spring brings the most reliable weather; Cancun's beaches can see seasonal sargassum from around May to October.`,
  },
  'impression-isla-mujeres-by-secrets': {
    activities: `This is one of the few large all-inclusive resorts actually on Isla Mujeres island rather than the mainland, reached by private boat transfer, which shapes the whole stay around a quieter, more insular island rhythm. On-site diving and snorkeling trips explore the reefs around the island (including the underwater sculpture museum, MUSA), while a spa, yoga classes, and a swim-up bar fill the rest of the day. Golf carts and bikes are the way to explore the island's town and Playa Norte beyond the resort.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Impression Isla Mujeres by Secrets is part of the Hyatt Inclusive Collection, reached via Cancun airport followed by a boat transfer to the island, about 25 minutes each way. It's adults-only, and its ratings are excellent nearly across the board, food, room, cleanliness, and service all rate highly, with the beach a shade behind Isla Mujeres' famous Playa Norte but still solid. It suits couples wanting an island retreat that still counts as an easy Cancun-area trip. Book the boat transfer times in advance, and aim for the November–April dry season for the smoothest crossings.`,
  },
  'el-dorado-seaside-palms': {
    activities: `El Dorado Seaside Palms is part of Karisma's "Unlimited-Luxury" El Dorado collection along the Riviera Maya, with thatched-roof suites, a swim-up bar, tennis, and a spa built around a gourmet, reservation-free dining concept. Watersports gear is available off the beach, and the surrounding area gives easy access to cenote diving, the Xel-Ha and Xcaret parks, and day trips to Tulum's ruins or Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This adults-only Karisma property sits along the El Dorado stretch of the Riviera Maya, reached via Cancun airport. The beach here is the clear weak point, one of among the lowest scores in our database, reflecting the narrower, sea-grass-prone sand typical of this section of coast, while atmosphere and food are middling too; rooms, service, and cleanliness are its strongest suits. It's a better fit for guests prioritizing food, suites, and quiet over a classic postcard beach. Winter and spring bring the calmest water; expect the most seaweed accumulation in mid-to-late summer.`,
  },
  'premium-level-at-barcelo-maya-palace': {
    activities: `Guests on the Premium Level get their own quieter pool and beach section within the much larger Barceló Maya complex, plus access to the full shared property: a lazy river, water slides, a kids' club and teen club, tennis, and multiple restaurants across the connected hotels. Snorkeling and diving trips run from the beach out to the reef, and the surrounding Riviera Maya adds cenotes, Tulum, and Xcaret as day-trip options.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This premium tier within the Barceló Maya Palace, in Puerto Aventuras on the Riviera Maya, is reached via Cancun airport. It's a family resort, and the ratings show a resort that's dependable rather than exceptional in any one category, food and atmosphere are the softest marks, while cleanliness and location hold up well; the appeal of the Premium Level is a step up in privacy and service over the base Barceló Maya rate. It suits families who want access to a big multi-hotel complex without giving up a quieter home base. Aim for the dry winter and spring months for the best beach conditions.`,
  },
  'paraiso-de-la-bonita-riviera-maya': {
    activities: `Now operating as Royalton Reserve Paraíso de la Bonita, part of Marriott's Luxury Collection, this boutique property reopened in 2026 with a new tower and saltwater pool added to its original mangrove-and-beach setting in Puerto Morelos. The spa is a genuine draw here, alongside quieter pools than the area's mega-resorts. Puerto Morelos' own reef (part of a protected marine park) is minutes away for snorkeling, and Cancun's Hotel Zone and Playa del Carmen are both short drives for nightlife or shopping.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This adults-only resort sits in Puerto Morelos, about 20 minutes from Cancun airport, making it one of the closer Riviera Maya options to fly into. Room quality and service both rate exceptionally well, and cleanliness is a genuine strength, while the beach is a middling mark, this stretch of Puerto Morelos coast is narrower and mangrove-fringed rather than the wide sand of the Hotel Zone. It suits couples wanting a boutique, spa-forward stay close to the airport over a sprawling resort footprint. The dry season from November to April is the most reliable window for calm seas.`,
  },
  'kempinski-hotel-cancun': {
    activities: `Kempinski Hotel Cancún sits on the Hotel Zone's beach with a strong family layout: a kids' club, tennis courts, a dive center for reef trips, and a heated pool alongside the spa. Its Kukulcan Boulevard location puts Cancun's malls, marina watersports operators, and the ferry to Isla Mujeres all within a short taxi ride, and it's a workable base for day trips to Chichén Itzá or Xcaret as well.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This European luxury chain's Cancun property is directly in the Hotel Zone, minutes from the international airport. Cleanliness and service both rate exceptionally well, and the beach itself is a genuine strength here, one of the better scores in our database for the Hotel Zone specifically, with food and rooms also solid. It's built for families as much as couples, with a more understated, less party-driven atmosphere than some Hotel Zone neighbors. November through April brings the calmest weather and least seaweed on the sand.`,
  },
  'grand-fiesta-americana-coral-beach': {
    activities: `This all-suite resort occupies a curved beachfront position at Punta Cancun, with one of the Hotel Zone's most established spas (Gem Spa) alongside a kids' club, tennis, and a dive center for reef excursions and deep-sea fishing charters. Its location at the Hotel Zone's narrowest point puts Cancun's convention center, marina, and nightlife strip within walking distance, with Isla Mujeres ferries and Xcaret day trips both easy add-ons.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Grand Fiesta Americana Coral Beach is a family-friendly, all-suite property in the heart of the Cancun Hotel Zone, a short ride from the airport. It's one of the more consistently strong performers in our database, with a genuinely good beach, high marks for location, cleanliness, and rooms, and food and service both dependable. It suits families and couples alike who want a central Hotel Zone address with a well-regarded spa. Visit November to April for the driest weather; the Caribbean side here can see periodic sargassum in the summer months.`,
  },
  'zoetry-villa-rolandi-isla-mujeres': {
    activities: `This 35-suite boutique hotel is reached by the resort's own yacht from the Cancun mainland, and that private-dock arrival sets the tone: quiet, wellness-oriented, and small in scale. Two à la carte restaurants (Swiss-Italian and Mexican-French) anchor the dining, while the Zoëtry Spa runs yoga, meditation, and thalassotherapy alongside kayaking and paddleboarding from the beach. Isla Mujeres' Playa Norte and the island's small downtown are both reachable by golf cart.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Zoëtry Villa Rolandi is an adults-only, boutique all-inclusive on Isla Mujeres, reached via Cancun airport and then the resort's private yacht, about 25 minutes from the mainland. Room quality and service both rate very highly, reflecting the intimacy of a 35-suite property, while the beach is a mid-pack score, this section of the island favors calm water over expansive sand. It suits couples specifically seeking a small, wellness-focused escape rather than a resort with extensive facilities. Book the yacht transfer times ahead, and target the dry season from November through April.`,
  },
  'the-explorean-cozumel': {
    activities: `The Explorean is built around included excursions rather than beach lounging: diving and snorkeling trips onto Cozumel's Palancar and Colombia reef walls, cycling, and other guided adventures are bundled into the stay, alongside a kids' club and spa. Cozumel's rocky ironshore coastline here means the resort leans hard into its dive program and excursions instead of a swimmable beach.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Reached via Cozumel's own international airport (a short ferry or flight from Cancun), The Explorean is a Karisma-family property that deliberately omits in-room TVs to push guests toward its excursion program. The beach score here is among the lowest in our database, a direct result of Cozumel's rugged coastline rather than a resort shortcoming, so this is a property for divers and adventure-minded families, not beach-seekers. Value, service, and cleanliness all rate well. Cozumel's diving is best April through August for visibility, though hurricane season (June–November) can disrupt boat trips.`,
  },
  'barcelo-maya-palace': {
    activities: `Barceló Maya Palace anchors one of the Riviera Maya's largest resort complexes, with a flowrider, mini golf, tennis, and a full kids'/teen club structure, plus shared access to sister hotels' pools and restaurants across the property. A dive center runs reef trips, and the surrounding area adds Tulum, Xcaret, and cenote tours as day trips from this stretch near the Barceló Maya coast, with Playa del Carmen also within reach for an evening out.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This family resort sits within the sprawling Barceló Maya complex, reached via Cancun airport, roughly an hour south along the coast. It's a good fit for families wanting scale, multiple pools, restaurants, and activities across a connected multi-hotel property, but the ratings show real tradeoffs: food and atmosphere are noticeably softer than cleanliness and room quality. It works better for guests prioritizing variety, activities, and value over refined dining or a boutique feel. Aim for November through April for the calmest beach conditions; this coast can see sargassum buildup in the summer months, which is worth checking before booking a beach-focused trip.`,
  },
  'majestic-elegance-costa-mujeres': {
    activities: `Majestic Elegance sits in the Costa Mujeres corridor north of Cancun, a newer and notably quieter stretch of coast than the Hotel Zone. Kids' and teens' clubs, a swim-up bar, and a spa cover the property, while the calm, current-free water here suits families with younger children particularly well. Isla Mujeres' ferry and Cancun's Hotel Zone are both a manageable drive away for a change of scene.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This family resort is in Playa Mujeres/Costa Mujeres, roughly 30–40 minutes from Cancun airport, north of the traditional Hotel Zone. Room quality, value, and cleanliness all rate strongly, with food and atmosphere a step behind, reasonable for a large family property. It suits families wanting the calmer waters and newer construction of the Costa Mujeres corridor over the busier Hotel Zone strip. November through April is the most reliable weather window, and the northern-facing beaches here tend to see less sargassum than areas further south.`,
  },
  'club-med-cancun': {
    activities: `Club Med's signature G.O. entertainment model runs the show here: flying trapeze, a sailing school, and age-segmented kids' clubs (including one for children under 4) alongside a more conventional waterpark, tennis, and a dive center. The resort sits at the southern end of the Hotel Zone near Punta Nizuc, putting it close to Cancun's underwater museum (MUSA) and reef snorkeling.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Club Med Cancun, reopened in 2021, sits at Punta Nizuc in the Hotel Zone, a short ride from the airport. Its beach and location both rate well, reflecting the appeal of this quieter southern stretch of the zone, while food and atmosphere sit a bit lower than the rest of the ratings, a common Club Med tradeoff for the activity-dense, all-ages format. It's built for families wanting structured activities and G.O.-led entertainment rather than a quiet couples retreat. November through April brings the driest, calmest conditions for water sports.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-palace-las-americas': {
    activities: `This adults-only Riu flagship sits on one of the Hotel Zone's better beaches, with an included dive program, fishing charters, and snorkeling gear available right off the sand. A swim-up bar, spa, gym, and nightly entertainment cover the property itself, and its central Hotel Zone position puts Cancun's convention center, marina watersports, and nightlife strip within easy walking or taxi reach, along with the ferry to Isla Mujeres for a day trip.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hotel Riu Palace Las Américas is an adults-only property in the Cancun Hotel Zone, minutes from the international airport. Its beach is a genuine strength, unusual for this stretch, alongside strong value and cleanliness scores, while food and atmosphere are more middling, typical for the reliable-but-unfussy Riu brand. It suits couples wanting Hotel Zone convenience and nightlife access without paying for a boutique property, and its central location makes it easy to walk to neighboring hotels' bars in the evening. Visit November through April for the calmest seas; summer can bring seasonal sargassum to this coast.`,
  },
  'catalonia-royal-tulum': {
    activities: `Despite the name, this adults-only property sits in Xpu-Ha, part of the Catalonia Riviera Maya complex, on a genuinely good stretch of beach with a dive center covering reef trips, plus a gym, evening entertainment, and a nightclub. The surrounding area gives access to Xpu-Ha's own beach clubs, Akumal's turtle bay, and Tulum's ruins and beach zone, all a short drive south, with cenotes also within easy reach for a day of freshwater swimming.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Catalonia Royal Tulum is located in Xpu-Ha on the Riviera Maya, not in Tulum itself, and is reached via Cancun airport, roughly 45 minutes north. The beach here is a real asset, one of the stronger scores in our database, while food and atmosphere trail behind cleanliness and value. It's an adults-only property that suits couples wanting straightforward beach time over elaborate dining or a large-scale resort feel. The dry season, November through April, offers the calmest water and generally clearer conditions for snorkeling; expect more seaweed on the sand from late spring into summer.`,
  },
  'hotel-xcaret-mexico': {
    activities: `Like its sister Arte property, Hotel Xcaret México bundles unlimited entry to Grupo Xcaret's parks, Xcaret, Xel-Ha, Xplor, and more, into the stay, alongside an extensive river-style pool system, a lazy river, water slides, and both kids' and teens' clubs. Bicycles, yoga, tennis, babysitting, and an adult-only pool round out the property, with nightly entertainment and a nightclub for evenings, and Playa del Carmen's town center a short drive away for Fifth Avenue shopping and restaurants.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This family resort in Playa del Carmen is reached via Cancun airport, about 45 minutes north, and its main draw is the included access to Grupo Xcaret's ecopark network rather than a conventional beach stay. Pool, atmosphere, and location all rate exceptionally well, with the beach itself a decent but not standout mark, worth knowing if beach lounging is the priority over park days. It's built for families wanting a park-and-pool vacation with excursions baked into the rate rather than booked separately at extra cost. Plan park days for the December–April dry season when trails and cenotes are most comfortable, and book Xcaret park slots early since capacity is limited.`,
  },
  'privilege-aluxes': {
    activities: `Privilege Aluxes is a boutique, adults-only property on Isla Mujeres with direct access to one of the island's calmer beaches, a genuine strength here given the sheltered, current-free waters typical of this side of the island. A dive center runs trips to nearby reefs and the underwater sculpture museum (MUSA), a swim-up bar and gym cover the property itself, and the island's Playa Norte and small downtown are both reachable by golf cart, bike, or a short taxi ride for a change of scene.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This resort sits on Isla Mujeres, reached via Cancun airport and a short ferry crossing, roughly 25 minutes each way from the mainland. The beach is the standout score here, among the better marks in this whole batch, while the pool rates lower by comparison, a reasonable tradeoff on an island known more for its sand than elaborate pool complexes. It's adults-only and suits couples wanting an island base with real beach time over a sprawling mainland resort. November through April is the calmest window for the ferry crossing and the beach itself, with fewer choppy-water days.`,
  },
  'playacar-palace': {
    activities: `Playacar Palace sits within the gated Playacar development just south of Playa del Carmen, with bikes available to explore the neighborhood's golf course and the Xaman-Ha bird aviary nearby. On-site, a kids' club, dive center, fishing charters, and swim-up bar cover the basics, snorkeling gear is available off the beach, and Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue is a short walk or taxi ride for shopping and restaurants beyond the resort gates.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This Palace Resorts family property is in Playacar, adjoining Playa del Carmen, reached via Cancun airport about 45 minutes north. Room quality, service, and cleanliness all rate strongly, while the pool and atmosphere are softer marks, a reasonable tradeoff given the appeal of walking distance to Playa del Carmen's town rather than an isolated resort strip. It suits families wanting resort amenities with an actual town, restaurants, and nightlife nearby rather than a self-contained property far from anything else. Aim for the dry season, November to April, for the most comfortable beach days and calmer water.`,
  },
  'ocean-allure-costa-mujeres': {
    activities: `This newly built adults-only property, H10's flagship Ocean Allure debut, centers on two main pools, a surf-style wave pool, and a lazy river, alongside a bowling alley, games room, and the Despacio Spa's water circuit and treatments. It's in the Costa Mujeres corridor, giving straightforward access to the calmer beaches north of Cancun and a short drive to the Hotel Zone or the Isla Mujeres ferry for a change of pace.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Ocean Allure Costa Mujeres opened in late 2025 as H10 Hotels' premium adults-only concept, north of Cancun and about 30–40 minutes from the airport. As a new resort it doesn't yet carry a long review history, but early ratings put location as a comparative weak point relative to its strong room quality and cleanliness, reflecting the Costa Mujeres corridor's distance from central Cancun rather than the resort itself. It suits couples wanting a large-scale, brand-new property with resort-park-style amenities. November through April is the most reliable weather window on this coast.`,
  },
  'hidden-beach-au-naturel-resort': {
    activities: `As Riviera Maya's clothing-optional resort, Hidden Beach's day-to-day centers on its naturist beach and pool areas, alongside a more conventional spa, gym, and swim-up bar for guests who want it. Nightly entertainment includes theme parties, and the surrounding El Dorado/Puerto Aventuras stretch of coast offers cenote and reef trips for anyone venturing beyond the property.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hidden Beach Au Naturel Resort sits in the El Dorado/Kantenah area of the Riviera Maya, reached via Cancun airport. It's an adults-only, clothing-optional property, a specific niche rather than a general beach resort, and the beach score reflects this stretch's narrower, sea-grass-prone sand rather than the naturist policy itself; service and cleanliness both rate well. It's intended for guests specifically seeking a naturist environment, not a fit for those uncomfortable with nudity on the beach and around pools. Winter and spring bring the calmest seas and least seaweed.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-palace-riviera-maya': {
    activities: `This family Riu sits in the Playacar area near Playa del Carmen, with swim-up rooms, a large pool complex with a water feature, and windsurfing and snorkeling gear available off the beach. A kids' club and pool slides cover younger children, a nightclub and nightly entertainment fill the evenings, while a dive center arranges reef trips, and Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue is a short ride away for restaurants and shopping beyond the resort.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hotel Riu Palace Riviera Maya is in Playa del Carmen, reached via Cancun airport, about 45 minutes north. It's a dependable, mid-pack performer across most categories, location and cleanliness lead, while food and atmosphere are more ordinary, in keeping with the reliable, no-surprises Riu formula found across the brand's Riviera Maya properties. It's a family property that suits travelers wanting straightforward value and beach access near Playa del Carmen's town center rather than a boutique or luxury tier stay. Visit November through April for the calmest beach conditions and least seaweed on the sand.`,
  },
  'majestic-mirage-costa-mujeres': {
    activities: `Majestic Mirage, sister property to Majestic Elegance next door, adds a flowrider and swim-up suites to the family formula, alongside kids' and teens' clubs, a spa, and a waterpark section for younger children. Rooms for larger families are available, evening entertainment fills the nights, and the calm Costa Mujeres water suits snorkeling and paddleboarding close to shore, with Isla Mujeres' ferry and the Cancun Hotel Zone both reachable by car for a day trip.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This family resort sits in the Costa Mujeres corridor north of Cancun, roughly 30–40 minutes from the airport. Room quality and cleanliness both rate strongly, with food and atmosphere trailing a bit, typical for a large all-inclusive at this tier and scale. It's a good match for families wanting swim-up suites, a flowrider, and space for bigger groups, alongside calmer, quieter beaches than the Hotel Zone offers further south. Aim for November through April for the most reliable weather on this stretch of coast, with less seaweed than areas closer to Tulum.`,
  },
  'paradisus-playa-del-carmen': {
    activities: `This is the family side (La Esmeralda) of the Paradisus Playa del Carmen complex, sharing grounds with its adults-only counterpart La Perla, and it leans into that family remit with a waterpark, kids' club (including one for under-4s), pool slides, and rooms built for larger groups. A dive center, babysitting, and watersports gear cover the beach and pool days, with a nightclub and nightly entertainment for evenings, and cenote tours, Xcaret, and Tulum's ruins all straightforward day trips from here.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Paradisus Playa del Carmen is a Meliá family property on the Riviera Maya, about 45 minutes from Cancun airport. Room quality and sleep quality both rate well, while the beach is a comparatively soft mark for this stretch of coast, worth knowing if beach time is the priority over pool and family facilities. It suits families wanting a full waterpark-style pool setup and shared access to the resort's adults-only sister property's restaurants when a night out without kids is wanted. Plan for the November–April dry season, with more seaweed likely on the sand in summer months.`,
  },
  'secrets-moxche-playa-del-carmen': {
    activities: `Secrets Moxché opened in 2022 with an unusual layout of seven pools designed to evoke natural cenotes, alongside eleven restaurants spanning French, Italian, Mexican, and Asian menus. Watersports like kayaking and snorkeling run from the beach, yoga and dance classes fill the days, and the resort includes discounted greens fees at three nearby golf courses, including El Camaleón at Mayakoba.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Secrets Moxché is an adults-only Hyatt Inclusive Collection resort about 10 minutes from downtown Playa del Carmen and 45 minutes from Cancun airport. Pool and cleanliness both rate exceptionally well, reflecting the cenote-inspired pool design, while the beach is a noticeably softer score, a real tradeoff to weigh against the strong food and room ratings. It suits couples wanting a newer, design-forward property with an emphasis on pools and dining over classic beach time. Aim for November through April for the calmest water and least seaweed.`,
  },
  'bahia-principe-escape-sian-ka-an': {
    activities: `This adults-only property is part of the large Bahía Príncipe Riviera Maya complex near the Sian Ka'an biosphere reserve, with a golf course, casino, and tennis on-site alongside the beach and pool. Excursions from here can run into the Sian Ka'an reserve itself for boat tours and wildlife-watching, in addition to the more standard Tulum ruins and cenote circuit.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Bahía Príncipe Escape Sian Ka'an sits in the Akumal area of the Riviera Maya, reached via Cancun airport. The beach score here is one of among the lowest in our database, reflecting a narrower, sea-grass-affected shoreline typical of this stretch, so this is better suited to guests prioritizing the golf course, casino, and pool over sand; service and value both rate well. It's an adults-only property for couples rather than families. Visit November through April for calmer water, and expect more seaweed accumulation in the summer months.`,
  },
  'hyatt-vivid-playa-del-carmen': {
    activities: `This adults-only property (formerly operating as a Hilton before its rebrand) sits on the Playa del Carmen coast with a full spa, yoga classes, tennis, and a swim-up bar. A nightclub and nightly entertainment cover the evenings, and Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue, along with cenote tours and Xcaret park, are all easy day trips from the property.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hyatt Vivid Playa del Carmen is reached via Cancun airport, about 45 minutes north. Room quality and cleanliness both rate strongly, while the beach is a clear weak point here, one of the softer scores in our database, worth factoring in if beach time matters most. It's adults-only and suits couples wanting proximity to Playa del Carmen's town and nightlife over a beach-first stay. The dry season, November through April, offers the calmest seas; expect more seaweed on the coast from late spring into summer.`,
  },
  'iberostar-waves-quetzal': {
    activities: `Part of Iberostar's large Playa del Carmen complex, this family property (recently rebranded from Iberostar Quetzal into the value-oriented Waves tier) offers a kids' club, teen club, tennis, a spa, and a dive center for reef trips, all set within a jungle-adjacent stretch of coast. Babysitting and evening entertainment round out the schedule, and shared access to the wider Iberostar complex's restaurants adds variety. Note that Iberostar has scheduled a full renovation of this property from mid-May through November 2026.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Iberostar Waves Quetzal sits within Iberostar's Playa del Carmen complex, reached via Cancun airport, roughly 45 minutes north. It's a family resort with solid location and value scores, while food and atmosphere are more middling, consistent with the brand's shift toward a budget-conscious, activity-driven Waves concept rather than the upscale Selection tier. Because of the announced 2026 renovation closure (mid-May to end of November), travelers should confirm current operating status before booking outside the winter high season. When open, November through April brings the calmest beach weather and least seasonal seaweed.`,
  },
  'iberostar-selection-paraiso-lindo': {
    activities: `Iberostar Selection Paraíso Lindo, in the Playa Paraíso section of Iberostar's Riviera Maya complex, adds a lazy river and dual waterparks (for both younger and older kids) to the family formula, alongside a golf course, dive center, babysitting, and kids' and teens' clubs. Evening entertainment and a swim-up bar cover the rest of the day, and its position within the larger Iberostar complex gives access to shared restaurants and the nearby Playa Paraíso golf club.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This family resort sits in Playa Paraíso, part of Iberostar's larger Riviera Maya complex, reached via Cancun airport, about 30–40 minutes north. Cleanliness and sleep quality both rate well, while food and atmosphere trail a bit, typical for a large multi-pool family property at this scale and price point. It suits families wanting waterpark-style amenities, golf access, and room for bigger groups within one gated complex rather than a smaller boutique stay. Visit November through April for the driest, calmest conditions; summer can bring seasonal seaweed to this coast.`,
  },
  'conrad-tulum-riviera-maya': {
    activities: `Conrad Tulum sits at the end of an isolated jungle drive in Chemuyil, with private plunge pools in many rooms, an extensive spa with sixteen treatment rooms, yoga classes, and a dive center for reef, snorkeling, and cenote trips. Bicycles are available to explore the surrounding area, a kids' club and pool slide cover younger guests, and Tulum's ruins, beach clubs, and restaurant scene are all a short drive south, with Akumal's turtle bay also nearby.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This family-friendly Hilton property is reached via Tulum International Airport, closer than Cancun for this location, in the more secluded Chemuyil area north of Tulum town. Room quality and cleanliness both rate exceptionally well, and food is strong too, while the beach is a middling mark, typical of this jungle-fringed section of coast rather than a resort shortcoming. It suits travelers wanting a quieter, more remote, design-forward base near Tulum's cultural sites over Cancun Hotel Zone-style convenience and crowds. November through April is the most reliable dry season window for this stretch of coast.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-palace-mexico': {
    activities: `Hotel Riu Palace Mexico is one of several Riu properties clustered along the Playa del Carmen beach, with shared-brand pool and beach access typical of the group, plus a kids' club, babysitting, dive center, and tennis on-site. Evening entertainment and a swim-up bar fill out the days, and Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue and ferries to Cozumel are both a short ride away for a day of shopping and diving beyond the resort.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This family resort sits in Playa del Carmen, reached via Cancun airport, about 45 minutes north. Location and cleanliness both rate well, while food and atmosphere are more ordinary, consistent with the reliable, value-driven Riu formula found across its Riviera Maya cluster of hotels. It's a solid choice for families wanting straightforward amenities and beach access near Playa del Carmen's town rather than an elaborate dining scene or boutique atmosphere. Aim for November through April for the calmest beach conditions and least seasonal seaweed on the sand.`,
  },
  'sls-playa-mujeres': {
    activities: `SLS Playa Mujeres, Ennismore's first all-inclusive under the SLS brand, brings a lifestyle-hotel sensibility to the format: 18 restaurant and bar concepts (including its signature Fi'lia, Cleo, and Privilege), a cinema, an outdoor theatre, and a dedicated kids' zone and playroom. A gym, wellness studios, spa, dive center, fishing charters, and golf access round out the property, set within the gated Playa Mujeres beach community north of Cancun, with a nightclub and evening entertainment for adults after dark.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This family resort opened recently in Playa Mujeres, roughly 30–40 minutes from Cancun airport, in a private gated beach community known for calm, uncrowded water and easy access to the Great Mayan Reef. Room quality, cleanliness, and food all rate strongly for a newer property, with atmosphere and service close behind. It suits families and design-conscious travelers wanting a more lifestyle-driven, nightlife-savvy take on all-inclusive rather than a traditional resort feel, while still offering full kids' facilities. November through April brings the most reliable weather on this coast, with calmer seas for beach days.`,
  },
  'secrets-the-vine-cancun': {
    activities: `Secrets The Vine is an adults-only resort in the Cancun Hotel Zone rather than the Riviera Maya proper, with a heated pool, gym, dive center for reef trips, room service, a nightclub, and nightly entertainment on-site. Its Hotel Zone position puts Cancun's marina watersports, malls, and the Isla Mujeres ferry all within a short taxi ride, and downtown Cancun's local restaurants are also easily reached for guests wanting to leave the resort for a night.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Secrets The Vine Cancun sits in the Hotel Zone, minutes from the international airport. The beach here is a genuine strength, notably better than many Hotel Zone neighbors, alongside strong room and cleanliness scores; food and atmosphere are solid without being standout. It's part of the Hyatt Inclusive Collection's Secrets brand, geared to couples wanting Hotel Zone convenience, nightlife access, and reliable beach conditions rather than the quieter Riviera Maya towns further south. Visit November through April for the calmest seas and least seasonal seaweed on Cancun's beaches.`,
  },
  'hyatt-vivid-grand-island': {
    activities: `This large adults-only property in the Cancun Hotel Zone centers on its pool and nightlife offering, with a gym, swim-up bar, buffet, spa, and nightly entertainment as the main draws. Its Hotel Zone address puts Cancun's marina, malls, and the ferry to Isla Mujeres within easy reach for guests wanting to leave the property, and downtown Cancun's restaurant scene is also a short taxi ride away for an evening out.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hyatt Vivid Grand Island sits in the Cancun Hotel Zone, a short ride from the airport. Rooms and cleanliness both rate very well, while the beach is a clear weak point here, one of the lower scores in our database, so guests should set expectations around the pool and property itself rather than the sand. It's an adults-only resort suited to couples focused on nightlife, pool time, and central Hotel Zone convenience over beach-first travel. November through April brings the calmest, driest conditions for this stretch of coast, with less chance of sargassum.`,
  },
  'barcelo-maya-caribe': {
    activities: `Barceló Maya Caribe is part of the same connected complex as the Palace, Colonial, and Tropical hotels, giving guests access to a flowrider, mini golf, tennis, and multiple pools across the property in addition to its own kids' club, dive center, snorkeling gear, and casino. Evening entertainment and a swim-up bar fill the rest of the schedule, reef snorkeling trips run from the beach, and Tulum, Xcaret, and cenote tours are all available as day-trip excursions.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This family resort sits in the Solidaridad area within the larger Barceló Maya complex, reached via Cancun airport, roughly an hour south. Cleanliness and location both rate reasonably well, while food and atmosphere are the softer marks, in keeping with the value-driven, activity-dense format of this complex rather than a refined dining destination. It suits families wanting resort-wide variety across several connected hotels, casino, and waterpark elements rather than a single boutique property. November through April is the most reliable window for calm beach conditions and least seaweed.`,
  },
  'blue-diamond-luxury-boutique-hotel': {
    activities: `This adults-only boutique hotel sits in 36 acres of jungle and garden just north of Playa del Carmen, with three restaurants, a spa offering hydrotherapy and sports massage, room service, and yoga and fitness classes as the main on-site draws. A dive center runs snorkeling and reef trips, bicycles are available to explore the grounds and nearby coast, and guests get access to the nearby El Camaleón golf course at Mayakoba, with Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue a short drive south.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Blue Diamond Luxury Boutique Hotel is BlueBay's flagship property, in the Riviera Maya near Playa del Carmen, reached via Cancun airport (about 40 minutes). Room quality, cleanliness, and sleep quality all rate well, while the beach is a middling mark, worth noting for a boutique property positioned more on style, gardens, and service than on a wide stretch of sand. It's an adults-only resort suited to couples wanting a smaller-scale, garden-set retreat with golf access nearby rather than a large-scale mega-resort. November through April brings the calmest, driest weather and least seaweed on the coast.`,
  },
  'temptation-cancun-resort': {
    activities: `Temptation leans into an adult-playful atmosphere with optional topless pool areas, themed parties, and pool games as the core of its entertainment program, alongside more conventional windsurfing, yoga classes, room service, and a swim-up bar. A gym and spa cover quieter daytime hours, and its Hotel Zone position makes Cancun's nightlife strip, malls, and marina watersports easy to reach for guests wanting a change of scene beyond the resort's own party calendar.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Temptation Cancun Resort is an adults-only property in the Hotel Zone, minutes from the airport, built specifically around a flirtatious, party-forward format rather than a quiet couples retreat. Value and location both rate well, while sleep quality is the softest mark, unsurprising given the late-night entertainment focus and pool-party culture. It's intended for guests specifically seeking that playful, adult-oriented atmosphere rather than a general-purpose family or quiet-couples beach resort, so it's worth knowing what you're booking into. November through April offers the calmest weather for daytime pool and beach activities.`,
  },
  'margaritaville-island-reserve-riviera-maya': {
    activities: `This adults-only Karisma/Margaritaville property is pool-first rather than beach-first: the resort has no direct beach access, but its restaurants and bars open right onto the pool deck, including Mexico's first LandShark brewery. A gym, yoga classes, and a spa round out the wellness side, evening entertainment and a nightclub fill the nights, and Puerto Morelos' protected reef and Cancun's Hotel Zone both a short drive away for guests wanting to swim or explore beyond the property.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Margaritaville Island Reserve Riviera Maya sits in Puerto Morelos, about 20 minutes from Cancun airport. Rooms here rate exceptionally well, and cleanliness and service are strong too, but the beach score is genuinely low because this property does not have direct beach access, a structural fact rather than a seasonal issue, so guests wanting sand and swimming should look to the family sister property nearby or plan beach club visits instead. It's adults-only and suits couples who want a Margaritaville-branded pool scene over a beach stay. November through April is the driest, most comfortable season generally on this coast.`,
  },
  'ocean-maya-royale': {
    activities: `Ocean Maya Royale, an H10 property just outside Playa del Carmen, centers on two outdoor pools, the Despacio Spa Centre, tennis, a swim-up bar, and a range of themed restaurants across the property. A dive center covers reef and fishing trips, and its location puts the 18-hole El Camaleón golf course and the Tres Ríos eco-park both under 10 minutes away, alongside easy access into Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue for restaurants and nightlife.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This adults-only H10 resort sits about 15 minutes north of Playa del Carmen, reached via Cancun airport (roughly 40 minutes). Value and location both rate well, while food and atmosphere are the softer marks in the lineup, along with a modest beach score typical of this stretch of coast. It suits couples wanting straightforward golf and spa access, plus proximity to Playa del Carmen's town, without paying for a flagship luxury property. Visit November through April for the calmest seas and least seaweed on the beach.`,
  },
  'trs-coral-hotel': {
    activities: `TRS Coral Hotel, part of Palladium's adults-only premium tier within the Grand Palladium Costa Mujeres complex, includes the Helios Beach Club, the Chic Cabaret gastro-show, and access to the Zentropia Spa's water circuit, sauna, and steam room. Tennis, a heated pool, a gym, room service, a swim-up bar, and nightly entertainment round out the property, with the calmer Costa Mujeres beaches just outside and Cancun's Hotel Zone under 30 minutes away for a change of scene.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This adults-only Palladium resort sits in Costa Mujeres, roughly 30 minutes from Cancun airport, within a private beachfront complex north of the city. Room quality and cleanliness both rate strongly, and the beach is a genuine strength here too, reflecting the calmer, less crowded northern coastline compared to the Hotel Zone. It suits couples wanting Palladium's higher "Infinite Indulgence" tier of service and dining over the group's standard Grand Palladium properties nearby. November through April brings the most dependable dry-season weather and calmest water, with less chance of sargassum than beaches farther south toward Playa del Carmen and Tulum.`,
  },
  'barcelo-maya-tropical': {
    activities: `Barceló Maya Tropical, in Puerto Aventuras within the larger Barceló Maya complex, adds a casino and mini golf to the shared amenities of its sister hotels, including a flowrider, water slides, tennis, a kids' club, and multiple pools accessible across the property. A dive center and snorkeling gear cover the beach, babysitting is available for parents' nights out, and cenote and Tulum day trips are easy to arrange from this stretch of the Riviera Maya.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This family resort is part of the Barceló Maya complex in Puerto Aventuras, reached via Cancun airport, roughly an hour south. Value and cleanliness both rate reasonably, while room quality and service trail the rest of this batch somewhat, worth weighing against the appeal of the complex's shared amenities and lower price point. It suits families wanting access to a large multi-hotel resort with casino, waterpark, and entertainment options included across several connected properties. Aim for November through April for the calmest beach weather on this coast.`,
  },
  'iberostar-waves-tucan': {
    activities: `Iberostar Waves Tucán, recently rebranded from Iberostar Tucán into the value-oriented Waves tier, sits within Iberostar's Playa del Carmen jungle-and-beach complex, with a kids' club, teen club, tennis, babysitting, a swim-up bar, and a dive center for reef trips. Evening entertainment and shared access to the wider Iberostar complex's restaurants add variety. Note that Iberostar has this property scheduled for a full renovation from mid-May through the end of November 2026.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This family resort is part of Iberostar's Playa del Carmen complex, reached via Cancun airport, about 45 minutes north. Location and value both rate decently, while food and atmosphere trail behind, consistent with the brand's shift toward a more budget-conscious, activity-driven concept under the Waves name rather than the upscale Selection tier. Given the announced 2026 renovation closure, confirm operating dates before booking travel outside the winter high season. When open, November through April brings the most reliable weather and calmest beach conditions, with the jungle setting staying green even in the drier months.`,
  },
  'iberostar-selection-paraiso-maya-suites': {
    activities: `This all-suite property in Iberostar's Playa Paraíso complex offers a lazy river, kids' and teens' clubs, babysitting, a swim-up bar, and golf access at the nearby Iberostar course, along with a dive center for reef trips. Evening entertainment and a spa round out the day, and its position within the larger Iberostar Riviera Maya development gives access to shared restaurants and waterpark facilities across the complex.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Iberostar Selection Paraíso Maya Suites sits in Playa Paraíso, part of Iberostar's larger Riviera Maya complex, reached via Cancun airport, roughly 30–40 minutes north. Cleanliness rates well, while sleep quality and atmosphere are more middling, typical for a large all-suite family property within a shared multi-hotel complex rather than a standalone boutique resort. It suits families wanting suite-style rooms with kitchenette-style space, plus access to a broader resort development's pools and kids' facilities. November through April offers the calmest, driest conditions on this stretch of coast.`,
  },
  'iberostar-waves-cozumel': {
    activities: `Iberostar Waves Cozumel sits on Cozumel island, with a dive center that's the real draw here given the island's famous reef walls (Palancar, Colombia, and Santa Rosa among them), alongside a kids' club, tennis, a swim-up bar, and evening entertainment. Snorkeling gear is available right off the property, and San Miguel town's shops, restaurants, and dive shops are a short drive for a change of pace from the resort itself.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This family resort is reached via Cozumel's own international airport, avoiding the Cancun-side ferry or flight connection that many Riviera Maya properties require. The beach score here is on the low side, typical of Cozumel's rockier west coast, so this is better suited to families prioritizing the island's exceptional diving and snorkeling over beach lounging; value and cleanliness both rate reasonably given the price point. April through August generally offers the best underwater visibility for diving and snorkeling trips, though hurricane season from June through November can occasionally disrupt boat excursions to outer reef sites.`,
  },
  'heaven-at-the-hard-rock-hotel-riviera-maya': {
    activities: `Heaven is the adults-only section of the Hard Rock Hotel Riviera Maya, with the brand's signature rock-memorabilia theming, a casino, and nightclub for evening entertainment, alongside a gym, dive center, tennis, room service, and fishing charters. Guests here also get access to the wider Hard Rock property's restaurants and pools in the Puerto Aventuras area of the coast, with cenote tours and Tulum's ruins both reachable as day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This adults-only section sits within the Hard Rock Hotel Riviera Maya complex, reached via Cancun airport, roughly an hour south. Service and value both rate well, while the beach is a noticeably soft mark for this stretch of coast, a real consideration if beach time is the priority over nightlife and casino access. It suits couples wanting Hard Rock's branded entertainment, nightlife, and larger-scale amenities over a quiet, low-key beach retreat. November through April brings the calmest seas and least seaweed on this part of the Riviera Maya.`,
  },
  'marriott-cancun': {
    activities: `This CasaMagna-style Marriott sits on genuinely good Hotel Zone sand, with a marina for fishing charters and watersports, a kids' club, an arcade, pool slides and a water feature, a heated pool, and a dive center for reef trips. Room service and a full-service spa round out the amenities, and its position gives easy access to Cancun's convention center and shopping malls, plus the ferry to Isla Mujeres for a day trip across the bay.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Marriott Cancun is a family resort in the Hotel Zone, close to the international airport. The beach here is a real strength, one of the better scores in our database, alongside strong cleanliness and service marks; the pool and atmosphere are a step behind by comparison, worth noting if pool time matters as much as beach time. It suits families wanting a dependable, brand-name property with genuinely good beach access in a central Hotel Zone location near restaurants and nightlife. Visit November through April for the calmest, driest conditions and least seaweed.`,
  },
  'ventus-ha-at-marina-el-cid-spa-and-beach-resort': {
    activities: `This El Cid property in Puerto Morelos centers on its own marina, with fishing charters and yacht excursions departing on-site, alongside a kids' and teens' club, water slides, a water feature, bicycles, and a spa. Snorkeling trips reach Puerto Morelos' protected reef, one of the closest good reef sites to Cancun airport, just offshore, and Cancun's Hotel Zone is a short drive for guests wanting a change of scene.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Ventus Ha' at Marina El Cid is a family resort in Puerto Morelos, about 20 minutes from Cancun airport, making it one of the more convenient Riviera Maya bases for a shorter transfer. Room quality and cleanliness both rate well, while the beach is a middling mark, typical of Puerto Morelos' narrower, mangrove-influenced shoreline compared to the open Hotel Zone sand further north. It suits families wanting marina access, boat excursions, and proximity to the airport over an expansive beach. November through April is the most reliable season for calm water.`,
  },
  'margaritaville-island-reserve-riviera-cancun': {
    activities: `Unlike its adults-only sister property next door, this family-friendly Margaritaville sits directly on the beach at Playa Punta Caracol, with four restaurants, six specialty bars, and four pools built around a relaxed, Jimmy Buffett-branded atmosphere. A kids' club, watersports gear, yoga classes, a dive center, and windsurfing cover the beach days, evening entertainment fills the nights, and Puerto Morelos' protected reef is a short swim or boat trip offshore.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Margaritaville Island Reserve Riviera Cancún is a family resort in Puerto Morelos, about 20 minutes from Cancun airport. Room quality rates very well, and cleanliness and service are both strong, while the beach is a comparatively soft mark for this stretch of coast, though notably this property does have genuine beach access, unlike its adults-only counterpart across the road. It suits families wanting the Margaritaville brand experience with real beach time close to the airport rather than a pool-only stay. November through April is the most dependable weather window on this coast.`,
  },
  'el-dorado-royale': {
    activities: `El Dorado Royale is Karisma's flagship "Unlimited-Luxury" property on this stretch of the Riviera Maya, with an over-water bar, a lazy river, and gourmet reservation-free dining as its signature features. A spa, tennis, room service, swim-up bar, evening entertainment, and fishing charters round out the property, with cenote tours and Tulum's ruins both available as day trips from this part of the coast near Puerto Aventuras.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This adults-only resort sits near Playa del Carmen on the Riviera Maya, reached via Cancun airport, roughly 45 minutes north. The beach is the clear weak point here, one of the lower scores in our database, reflecting the narrower, sea-grass-prone sand common along this part of the coast, while food, cleanliness, and service all rate well above it. It suits couples prioritizing dining, the lazy-river pool experience, and Karisma's gourmet-inclusive concept over a classic beach stay. November through April brings the calmest water and least seaweed on the sand.`,
  },
  'moon-palace-the-grand-cancun': {
    activities: `Moon Palace's Grand tower is part of a sprawling, resort-park-style complex with a Jack Nicklaus-designed golf course, a flowrider, an arcade, and separate waterparks for younger and older kids, alongside multiple pools and an adult-only pool section. It's less a single hotel than a small self-contained destination, with Cancun's Hotel Zone and airport both a short drive away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Moon Palace The Grand sits in Cancun, close to the international airport, and is part of the larger Moon Palace resort complex. The beach score here is the softest mark by a wide margin, reflecting the property's emphasis on its golf course, pools, and waterpark facilities over open-ocean beachfront; rooms and cleanliness both rate very well by contrast. It's built for families wanting an all-in-one resort destination with golf and kids' amenities rather than a beach-first stay. November through April offers the most reliable weather for golf and pool days alike.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-latino': {
    activities: `Hotel Riu Latino is one of the newer Riu additions serving the Playa Mujeres/Costa Mujeres corridor north of Cancun, with a gym, buffet, swim-up bar, nightclub, and nightly entertainment as the main on-site draws. The calmer northern coastline here suits swimming and snorkeling close to shore, with Isla Mujeres' ferry a manageable drive away and Cancun's Hotel Zone reachable for a day of shopping or nightlife beyond the resort.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This adults-only Riu property sits in the Playa Mujeres area, roughly 30–40 minutes from Cancun airport. Room quality and value both rate strongly, while atmosphere and pool are more middling, in keeping with the reliable, straightforward Riu format found across the brand's Mexico portfolio. It suits couples wanting a newer property in the quieter, less-developed Costa Mujeres corridor over the busier Hotel Zone strip further south. November through April is the most reliable season for calm water and dry weather on this stretch of coast.`,
  },
}
